Rough Draft

Luke Anderson, Jeremy Earnst, Ryan Smith

Abstract

Using data from Bart Torviks T-Rank website and college basketball ratings system, we analyze the impact of different regular season metrics on March Madness tournament success during the 2020-2021 college basketball season. We incorporate different statistical methods into our analysis, including graphical representation, summary statistics, correlations, and linear regression models. We find that it is actually quite hard to predict tournament success based on these metrics: we find that only barthag rating, tournament seed, expected wins, offensive and defensive efficiency, and EFG and EFGD % are significant predictors of tournament wins (and its worth noting that some of these metrics may be linearly dependent upon one another). Other variables (like a teams turnover rate and offensive rebounding) seem to have a significant impact on a teams probability of making the tournament, but beyond these the other results that we find in this category are bogged down by modeling issues, making it hard to be sure of the conclusions.

From all of this, we can anticlimactically conclude that having a good offense and a good defense helps teams have more tournament success. However, in our work we were able to helpfully debunk the myth that strength of schedule and offensive tempo are significant factors in tournament success, a result which may surprise most college basketball fans. Finally, we note that our own created metric of expected wins was a very good predictor of tournament success, and we hope that such a discovery could be used in the future as a contribution to the world of sports statistics.

Introduction

March Madness is a knockout style tournament in which 64 college basketball teams compete to be the US national champions. The tournament, taking place annually during the titular month of March, draws millions of viewers and over a billion dollars in revenue each year. With all those eyes and all those dollars, everyone is looking for a way to gain an edge on the tournaments results. Whether its teams trying to outsmart the competition, bookies working to set odds, or an average Joe trying to find the perfect bracket, everyone wants to know what will happen. With the advent of moneyball and data driven sports, one of the many new approaches to predicting March Madness is statistical analysis. It is into this world that we step as we analyze data from the 2021 college basketball season.

(NOTE: For simplicity, we have removed the four teams that lost in the play-in games from the tournament data.)

Modeling

Outcome: Tournament Wins

We will start simple, and regress the number of tourney wins on the teams tourney seed:

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = wins_tourney ~ tourney_seed, data = CBBtourney)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -1.8088 -0.7941 -0.1746  0.4766  4.0643 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)   2.06250    0.31784   6.489 1.63e-08 ***
## tourney_seed -0.12684    0.03287  -3.859 0.000274 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.212 on 62 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1937, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1806 
## F-statistic: 14.89 on 1 and 62 DF,  p-value: 0.0002741

Here find a very low p-value, giving us strong reason to reject H0. From the regression we can say that improving a teams seed by one unit would, on average, result in .12684 more wins in the tournament.

Next, we will regress the number of tourney wins on the teams pre-tournament barthag:

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = wins_tourney ~ barthag, data = CBBtourney)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -1.3556 -1.0298 -0.1952  0.5228  4.5403

## Coefficients:

## barthag       3.3141     1.0565   3.137  0.00261 **
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.254 on 62 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.137,  Adjusted R-squared:  0.1231 
## F-statistic: 9.841 on 1 and 62 DF,  p-value: 0.00261

Once again, we find reason to reject H0, with a low p-value of .00261. This regression says that a .1 unit increase in pre-tourney barthag rating results in, on avergage, .33141 more wins in the tourney.

Next, lets take a look at how good our expected tourney wins metric is at predicting actual tournament wins. Remember that this metric includes both seed and barthag in its formula, so we would expect it to have similar results to the first couple of regressions:

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = wins_tourney ~ expwins_tourney, data = CBBtourney)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -2.6201 -0.6243 -0.4162  0.4333  3.3929 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                 Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)       0.3305     0.1761   1.877   0.0653 .  
## expwins_tourney   0.6745     0.1158   5.823 2.22e-07 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.085 on 62 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.3535, Adjusted R-squared:  0.3431 
## F-statistic:  33.9 on 1 and 62 DF,  p-value: 2.216e-07

As expected, we have a tiny p-value, meaning that our predictor is doing its job (we can reject H0 with confidence). This says that for every 1 additional expected win, a team will, on average, win .6745 more actual games in the tournament. Not bad at all! Its also worth noting that the R-Squared value is significantly higher here (.3535 compared with .1937 and .1370 in the first two regressions).

Next, lets see how offensive and defensive efficiency affect tourney wins.

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = wins_tourney ~ adj_oe + adj_de, data = CBBtourney)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max

## Coefficients:

## adj_de      -0.168288   0.050550  -3.329  0.00148 ** 
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.113 on 61 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.3309, Adjusted R-squared:  0.309 
## F-statistic: 15.09 on 2 and 61 DF,  p-value: 4.748e-06

Shocker! If you have a good offense and a good defense, youll win more tournament games! Weve solved it, guys! Bet you didnt see that one coming. Both of these tests have low p-values, giving us good reason to reject H0. For every 10-unit increase in adjusted offense, a team wins, on average, 1.49697 more tournament games. For every 10-unit decrease in adjusted defense (lower is better), a team wins, on average, 1.68288 more tournament games.

One common hypothesis is that if a team plays a higher number of quality games in a season, they are more prepared for the big dance because theyve played stiffer competition. Lets test that out:

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = wins_tourney ~ qual_games, data = CBBtourney)

## F-statistic: 0.8342 on 1 and 62 DF,  p-value: 0.3646

Surprisingly, we fail to reject this H0 (p-value of .365). Perhaps playing tough regular season games isnt as important as it is made out to be.

Unsurprisingly (more variables means higher variances and bigger confidence intervals), we dont find anything very helpful here. EFGD_perc is significant at the alpha=.1 level, but besides that it doesnt seem like this adds much more information. Its worth noting that it only has an R-Squared of .4238, not much higher than what we had when we regressed tourney wins only on expected tourney wins. However, from the F-test for goodness of fit gives a p-value of .007425, demonstrating that it is likely that at least one of the variables is significantly contributing to the prediction of wins_tourney.

## TORD         0.0584356  0.0752710   0.776   0.4409   
## ORB          0.0598672  0.0432136   1.385   0.1716   
## DRB          0.0203190  0.0579879   0.350   0.7274   
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 1.2 on 54 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.3117, Adjusted R-squared:  0.197 
## F-statistic: 2.717 on 9 and 54 DF,  p-value: 0.01092

Thats more like it. EFG_perc and EFGD_perc both appear to have small but signfiicant impacts at the alpha=.1 confidence level. Once again, good offense and good defense wins games! Another fact worth noting is that this regression is almost certain that the teams tempo (speed of play) has virtually no effect on tourney wins (p-value of .9886 and a beta_hat of .0009996). This appears to debunk another narrative that is commonly stated, that teams with either super fast offenses or teams with a grind-it-out style of play have an advantage in the tournament.

Outcome: Making The Tournament

(NOTE: The following regressions are called linear probability models, which are required in this case because the outcome variable, make_tourney, is a dummy variable. This means that R-Squared is mostly useless, since the outcome is a dummy variable but the estimate of the dummy outcome is continuous.)

Weve looked at performance in the tournament, but it might also be helpful to zoom out and discover what metrics might be good predictors of making the tournament in the first place. Lets start with barthag:

## Call:
## lm(formula = make_tourney ~ barthag, data = CBBpreTourney)

## F-statistic: 181.8 on 1 and 341 DF,  p-value: < 2.2e-16

The way to interpret this result is as follows: a 1-unit increase in barthag (in this case, since barthag only ranges from 0-1, this would be the biggest increase possible) increases the probability of a team making the NCAA tournament by .87230 (out of 1). This result is significant (reject H0) at all major significance levels.

From these results, it seems to me that teams who are more likely to make the tournament are teams who shoot well, defend shots well, and maximize the number of possessions (and thus shots) that you have (take care of the ball!).

Lastly, and just as a note of interest, lets see if the number of games played during the season has any impact on making the tournament:

## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = make_tourney ~ totalgames_pre_tourney, data = CBBpreTourney)
## 
## Residuals:
##      Min       1Q   Median       3Q      Max 
## -0.44111 -0.24508 -0.14706  0.01631  1.04898 
## 
## Coefficients:
##                         Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept)            -0.539074   0.110365  -4.884  1.6e-06 ***
## totalgames_pre_tourney  0.032673   0.004888   6.684  9.5e-11 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
## 
## Residual standard error: 0.3674 on 341 degrees of freedom
## Multiple R-squared:  0.1158, Adjusted R-squared:  0.1132 
## F-statistic: 44.68 on 1 and 341 DF,  p-value: 9.503e-11

Interesting! It seems that there is a significant impact of playing more games on a teams chances of making the tournament (p-value=9.5e-11). Every additional game adds .032673 probability of making the tournament. However, we would be hesitant to claim a causal relationship here. We probably have an example of reverse causuality here: we would guess that it is more likely that good teams schedule more games, rather than scheduling more games resulting in better teams.

Results

In terms of predicting tourney wins, the only statistically significant predictors proved to be seed, barthag, expected wins (which is calculated using seed and barthag), adjusted offense, and adjusted defense (and the latter two are used in part to calculate barthag). When we included only in-game statistics, we found that EFG and EFGD percentages were significant predictors as well. Contrary to many narratives spun in the college basketball world, number of quality games, strength of schedule (non-conference and conference), and the teams adjusted tempo had no discernible impact on tournament wins, a finding which many college basketball fans might find surprising.

Predicting overperformance and underperformance proved to be tougher: none of the above metrics did a good job of predicting WTOE, although the opponents free throw rate during the regular season was significant at the alpha=.1 level (why? who knows!). However, this lack of predictive ability isnt shocking: it is called March Madness, after all.

In terms of improving the odds of making the tournament, we found similar results, with barthag, adj_oe, adj_de, and EFG and EFGD percentages all having signficant impacts on making the tournament. Additionally, qual_games, conf_sos, totalgames_pre_tourney, TOR, ORB, and DRB show somewhat significant or significant effects. However, we have reason to doubt some of these results because of issues with the linear probability model as well as reverse causality.

Conclusion

March Madness is an exciting experience, and the recent improvements in sports statistics have enabled us to study the game more closely in order to look for ways that teams can improve their tournament performances. In order to find insights in the data, we used summary statistics, graphical representations, and linear modeling to determine if there were certain metrics from the 2020-2021 college basketball that were statistically significant predictors of March Madness success, which we measured in terms of making the tournament, how many tournament games that tournament teams won, and tournament teams wins over expected. Unfortunately, but perhaps unsurprisingly, we did not find any earth-shattering or sport-altering revelations about the secret to March Madness success. It seems that if there is a secret, its having a highly-rated offense and a highly-rated defense (wow!). However, we were able to debunk several street myths: we found little evidence that strength of schedule metrics (including number of quality games, non-conference strength of schedule, and conference strength of schedule) nor tempo/pace-of-the-offense metrics have a significant impact on tournament success. Finally, its worth noting that our expected wins metric was a strong predictor of tournament success and, from the eye test, seems like a useful contribution to the study of college basketball statistics.
